# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: coaxial-power-connector
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The **Anderson Powerpole** is a family of electrical connectors by Anderson Power Products (APP), although plug compatible connectors are now available from alternate sources.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Specific variants of this series of connectors have become de facto standards for conveying "higher power" direct current (DC) electrical power, although these standards are inconsistent and sometimes ignored.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Powerpole connectors are hermaphroditic, with "cis" connectivity (pin 1 on one connector mates with pin 1 on the other connector, and pin 2 with pin 2), thus avoiding the need to worry about which end is the plug and which the socket, or which end has the correct polarity.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] This is in contrast to the two-wire trailer plug, which has "trans" connectivity (pin 1 on each connector mates with pin 2 on the other).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Powerpole connectors are available with current ratings of up to 180 amperes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The 15/30/45 ampere-rated connectors are the most common, using the same plastic housing and differing only in the metal contact inserted into the housing.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The contact is selected based on the ampacity and wire gauge.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The colors can be used to signify signal types (power, speaker, logic, microphone audio, etc.) or differing voltages.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Powerpole connectors can be attached side to side and also stacked on top of each other to make, for example, four connections with one plug insertion.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The contacts are rated for 100,000 no-load insertions and 250 hot-plugs at full load.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] They range from 50 to 500 amps, 600 volts.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Some of Anderson's earlier patents have expired, thus other manufacturers have released plug-compatible connectors, such as "AMP Power Series" by Tyco / TE Connectivity, Sermos, and Lightspeed.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Powerpole connector was designed and patented by "Albert & J M Anderson Mfg Comp", then more recently by "Anderson Power Products".
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Many companies in the amateur astronomy space have adopted Powerpole connectors, as a large number of astronomical devices use 12-volts, and Powerpole connectors offer a low cost and easy solution to make adaptors, extensions, and distribution panels.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Powerpole connector has been adopted by many segments of the Amateur Radio (Ham Radio) community as their standard 12-volt DC power connector for everything from radios to DC power sources to accessories.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Three notable groups are the Amateur Radio Emergency Service (ARES), the Radio Amateur Civil Emergency Service (RACES) and the Wireless Institute Civil Emergency Network (WICEN).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Standardization allows equipment owned by different hams to be used together without needing adapters in emergencies, at public service events, at field day, during contests, when borrowing equipment, etc.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Anderson Powerpole connector is more expensive than the older de facto standards of the two-wire trailer plug and the Molex connector, but provides a more reliable electrical connection (both mechanically and electrically), and is easier to adapt to a wider range of wire gauges.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Another advantage over the older trailer or Molex connectors is the Powerpole's superior ratings to withstand 100,000 no-load insertions and 250 hot-plugs at full load.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Many pieces of amateur radio equipment run on 12-volt DC automotive voltage, which is also called 13.8-volt DC.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The voltage delivered by a lead–acid battery with six-cells used as an automotive battery will vary depending on various electrical loads in a vehicle.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Without loads the battery will float from 11.7 to 12.8 volts, and while charging from an alternator the voltage will increase to 13.8–14.4 volts DC.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] For use in amateur radio, the community has adopted a standard color code, polarity, and specific physical arrangement for assembling pairs of Powerpole connectors.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The standard is red positive and black negative.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] When viewed from the contact side, a mnemonic for remembering the arrangement is: "Red [on] Right — Tongue [on] Top" (note the first letter alliteration).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] West Mountain Radio, a major amateur radio supplier, has had a few 24 V DC products in their catalog for over a decade.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] They incorporate a 24 volt standard that has the orange body as +24 volts.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] An orange and black pair would be +24 volts on the orange and ground on the black.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] In model railways, the NTRAK Modular Railroading Society adopted the Powerpole PP30 connector as a recommend practice in 2005. and as a standard in 2011.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The use of the older Cinch-Jones connector has been deprecated, but is still permitted on legacy modules.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] However, the owner of a module with Cinch-Jones plugs is now required to provide adapter cables to the newer standard.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] North Raleigh Model Railroad Club (NRMRC) also uses Anderson Powerpole connectors.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Free-mo modular standard adopted Powerpole as the new connector standard as of 1 July 2015, with a one-year transition period to convert existing Jones connectors.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The connectors are used by some robot builders, including the FIRST Robotics Competition, MATE ROV Competition, and R2-D2 Builders Club.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The Powerpole connectors are used by radio control (R/C) model hobbyist clubs.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] They may be known as "SB" connectors or "Sermos" connectors with the suppliers in that community.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Some buildings including data centers are increasingly designed for 380 V DC electric power distribution, as a way of improving electrical efficiency.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] DC power distribution has resulted in the need to standardize a Low Voltage (LV) connector with an integral ground conductor, which is safe for use by untrained personnel.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] The tendency of DC connectors to spark when disconnected from an inductive load requires the connector's insulating housing to contain the plasma arc, in addition to normal requirements such as preventing accidental finger contact.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/anderson-powerpole] Examples of such connectors are the Anderson Powerpole Pak connectors and the SDG (Saf-D-Grid) connector, designed with the form factor of an IEC C13 connector.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Arduino board designs use a variety of microprocessors and controllers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The boards are equipped with sets of digital and analog input/output (I/O) pins that may be interfaced to various expansion boards ('shields') or breadboards (for prototyping) and other circuits.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The boards feature serial communications interfaces, including Universal Serial Bus (USB) on some models, which are also used for loading programs.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The microcontrollers can be programmed using the C and C++ programming languages (Embedded C), using a standard API which is also known as the **Arduino Programming Language**, inspired by the Processing language and used with a modified version of the Processing IDE.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In addition to using traditional compiler toolchains, the Arduino project provides an integrated development environment (IDE) and a command line tool developed in Go.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino project began in 2005 as a tool for students at the Interaction Design Institute Ivrea, Italy, aiming to provide a low-cost and easy way for novices and professionals to create devices that interact with their environment using sensors and actuators.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Common examples of such devices intended for makers include simple robots, thermostats, and motion detectors.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The name *Arduino* comes from the Bar di Re Arduino, where some of the project's founders used to meet.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] This bar is in Ivrea, Italy and was named after Arduin.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino project was started at the Interaction Design Institute Ivrea (IDII) in Ivrea, Italy.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] At that time, the students used a BASIC Stamp microcontroller at a cost of $50.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In 2004, Hernando Barragán created the development platform *Wiring* as a Master's thesis project at IDII, under the supervision of Massimo Banzi and Casey Reas.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Casey Reas is known for co-creating, with Ben Fry, the Processing development platform.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The project goal was to create simple, low cost tools for creating digital projects by non-engineers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Wiring platform consisted of a printed circuit board (PCB) with an ATmega128 microcontroller, an IDE based on Processing and library functions to easily program the microcontroller.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In 2005, Massimo Banzi, with David Mellis, another IDII student, and David Cuartielles, extended Wiring by adding support for the cheaper ATmega8 microcontroller.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The new project, forked from Wiring, was called *Arduino*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The initial Arduino core team consisted of Massimo Banzi, David Cuartielles, Tom Igoe, Gianluca Martino, and David Mellis.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Following the completion of the platform, lighter and less expensive versions were distributed in the open-source community.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] It was estimated in mid-2011 that over 300,000 official Arduinos had been commercially produced, and in 2013 that 700,000 official boards were in users' hands.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In early 2008, the five co-founders of the Arduino project created a company, Arduino LLC, to hold the trademarks associated with Arduino.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The manufacture and sale of the boards were to be done by external companies, and Arduino LLC would get a royalty from them.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The founding bylaws of Arduino LLC specified that each of the five founders transfer ownership of the Arduino brand to the newly formed company.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] At the end of 2008, Gianluca Martino's company, Smart Projects, registered the Arduino trademark in Italy and kept this a secret from the other co-founders for about two years.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] This was revealed when the Arduino company tried to register the trademark in other areas of the world (they originally registered only in the US), and discovered that it was already registered in Italy.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Negotiations with Martino and his firm to bring the trademark under the control of the original Arduino company failed.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In 2014, Smart Projects began refusing to pay royalties.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] They then appointed a new CEO, Federico Musto, who renamed the company *Arduino SRL* and created the website *arduino.org*, copying the graphics and layout of the original *arduino.cc*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] This resulted in a rift in the Arduino development team.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In January 2015, Arduino LLC filed a lawsuit against Arduino SRL.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In May 2015, Arduino LLC created the worldwide trademark **Genuino**, used as brand name outside the United States.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] At the World Maker Faire in New York on 1 October 2016, Arduino LLC co-founder and CEO Massimo Banzi and Arduino SRL CEO Federico Musto announced the merger of the two companies, forming Arduino AG.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Around that same time, Massimo Banzi announced that in addition to the company a new Arduino Foundation would be launched as "a new beginning for Arduino", but this decision was withdrawn later.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In April 2017, Wired reported that Musto had "fabricated his academic record...
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] On his company's website, personal LinkedIn accounts, and even on Italian business documents, Musto was, until recently, listed as holding a Ph.D. from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In some cases, his biography also claimed an MBA from New York University." Wired reported that neither university had any record of Musto's attendance, and Musto later admitted in an interview with Wired that he had never earned those degrees.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The controversy surrounding Musto continued when, in July 2017, he reportedly pulled many open source licenses, schematics, and code from the Arduino website, prompting scrutiny and outcry.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] By 2017 Arduino 'AG' owned many Arduino trademarks.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In July 2017 BCMI, founded by Massimo Banzi, David Cuartielles, David Mellis and Tom Igoe, acquired Arduino AG and all the Arduino trademarks.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Fabio Violante is the new CEO replacing Federico Musto, who no longer works for Arduino AG.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In October 2017, Arduino announced its partnership with Arm Holdings (ARM).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The announcement said, in part, "ARM recognized independence as a core value of Arduino ... without any lock-in with the ARM architecture".
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Arduino intends to continue to work with all technology vendors and architectures.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Under Violante's guidance, the company started growing again and releasing new designs.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Genuino trademark was dismissed and all products were branded again with the Arduino name.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In August 2018, Arduino announced its new open source command line tool (arduino-cli), which can be used as a replacement of the IDE to program the boards from a shell.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In February 2019, Arduino announced its IoT Cloud service as an extension of the Create online environment.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] As of February 2020, the Arduino community included about 30 million active users based on the IDE downloads.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In October 2025 it was announced that Arduino has been acquired, for an as yet undisclosed amount, by the American semiconductor multinational Qualcomm.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The hardware reference designs are distributed under a Creative Commons Attribution Share-Alike 2.5 license and are available on the Arduino website.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Layout and production files for some versions of the hardware are also available.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Although the hardware and software designs are freely available under copyleft licenses, the developers have requested the name *Arduino* to be exclusive to the official product and not be used for derived works without permission.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The official policy document on the use of the Arduino name emphasizes that the project is open to incorporating work by others into the official product.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Several Arduino-compatible products commercially released have avoided the project name by using various names ending in *-duino*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Most Arduino boards consist of an Atmel 8-bit AVR microcontroller (ATmega8, ATmega168, ATmega328, ATmega1280, or ATmega2560) with varying amounts of flash memory, pins, and features.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The 32-bit Arduino Due, based on the Atmel SAM3X8E was introduced in 2012.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The boards use single or double-row pins or female headers that facilitate connections for programming and incorporation into other circuits.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] These may connect with add-on modules termed *shields*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Multiple and possibly stacked shields may be individually addressable via an I²C serial bus.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Most boards include a 5 V linear regulator and a 16 MHz crystal oscillator or ceramic resonator.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Some designs, such as the LilyPad, run at 8 MHz and dispense with the onboard voltage regulator due to specific form factor restrictions.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Arduino microcontrollers are pre-programmed with a bootloader that simplifies the uploading of programs to the on-chip flash memory.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The default bootloader of the Arduino Uno is the Optiboot bootloader.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Boards are loaded with program code via a serial connection to another computer.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Some serial Arduino boards contain a level shifter circuit to convert between RS-232 logic levels and transistor–transistor logic (TTL serial) level signals.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Current Arduino boards are programmed via Universal Serial Bus (USB), implemented using USB-to-serial adapter chips such as the FTDI FT232.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Some boards, such as later-model Uno boards, substitute the FTDI chip with a separate AVR chip containing USB-to-serial firmware, which is reprogrammable via its own ICSP header.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Other variants, such as the Arduino Mini and the unofficial Boarduino, use a detachable USB-to-serial adapter board or cable, Bluetooth or other methods.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] When used with traditional microcontroller tools, instead of the Arduino IDE, standard AVR in-system programming (ISP) programming is used.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino board exposes most of the microcontroller's I/O pins for use by other circuits.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The *Diecimila*, *Duemilanove*, and current *Uno* provide 14 digital I/O pins, six of which can produce pulse-width modulated(PWM) signals, and six analog inputs, which can also be used as six digital I/O pins.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] These pins are on the top of the board, via female 0.1-inch (2.54 mm) headers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Several plug-in application shields are also commercially available.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino Nano and Arduino-compatible Bare Bones Board and Boarduino boards may provide male header pins on the underside of the board that can plug into solderless breadboards.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Many Arduino-compatible and Arduino-derived boards exist.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Some are functionally equivalent to an Arduino and can be used interchangeably.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Many enhance the basic Arduino by adding output drivers, often for use in school-level education, to simplify making buggies and small robots.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Others are electrically equivalent, but change the form factor, sometimes retaining compatibility with shields, sometimes not.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Some variants use different processors, of varying compatibility.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] In addition to hardware variations, open source libraries have been developed to support Arduino hardware in EDA tools.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] One such project provides KiCad schematic symbols and PCB footprints for Arduino modules, expansion boards, and connectors, making it easier for engineers to integrate Arduino into their designs.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The original Arduino hardware was manufactured by the Italian company Smart Projects.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Some Arduino-branded boards have been designed by the American companies SparkFun Electronics and Adafruit Industries.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] As of 2016, 17 versions of the Arduino hardware have been commercially produced.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Arduino shields are add-on boards that stack onto Arduino mainboards to extend their functionality for specific tasks.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Common uses include controlling DC motors for a robot, for 3D printer, adding a LCD display, enabling Ethernet connectivity, providing GPS/ GNSS navigation and converting pin headers into Grove connectors.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Shields are typically designed and manufactured by third-party hardware companies, including SparkFun Electronics, Adafruit Industries, Seeed Studio, and Cytron Technologies, among others.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Several shields can also be made do it yourself (DIY).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] A program for Arduino hardware may be written in any programming language with compilers that produce binary machine code for the target processor.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Atmel provides a development environment for their 8-bit AVR and 32-bit ARM Cortex-M based microcontrollers: AVR Studio (older) and Atmel Studio (newer).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino integrated development environment (IDE) is a cross-platform application (for Microsoft Windows, macOS, and Linux) that is based on *Processing IDE* which is written in Java.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] It uses the *Wiring* API as programming style and HAL.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] It includes a code editor with features such as text cutting and pasting, searching and replacing text, automatic indenting, brace matching, and syntax highlighting, and provides simple *one-click* mechanisms to compile and upload programs to an Arduino board.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] It also contains a message area, a text console, a toolbar with buttons for common functions and a hierarchy of operation menus.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The source code for the IDE is released under the GNU General Public License, version 2.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino IDE supports the languages C and C++ using special rules of code structuring.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino IDE supplies a software library from the Wiring project, which provides many common input and output procedures.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] User-written code only requires two basic functions, for starting the sketch and the main program loop, that are compiled and linked with a program stub *main()* into an executable cyclic executive program with the GNU toolchain, also included with the IDE distribution.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino IDE employs the program *avrdude* to convert the executable code into a text file in hexadecimal encoding that is loaded into the Arduino board by a loader program in the board's firmware.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] An initial alpha preview of a new Arduino IDE was released on October 18, 2019, as Arduino Pro IDE.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The beta preview was released on March 1, 2021, renamed IDE 2.0.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] On September 14, 2022, the Arduino IDE 2.0 was officially released as stable.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The system still uses Arduino CLI (Command Line Interface), but improvements include a more professional development environment and autocompletion support.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The application frontend is based on the Eclipse Theia Open Source IDE.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] One important feature Arduino IDE 2.0 provides is the debugging feature.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] It allows users to single-step, insert breakpoints or view memory.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Debugging requires a target chip with debug port and a debug probe.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The official Arduino Zero board can be debugged out of the box.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Other official Arduino SAMD21 boards require a separate SEGGER J-Link or Atmel-ICE.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] For a 3rd party board, debugging in Arduino IDE 2.0 is also possible as long as such board supports GDB, OPENOCD and has a debug probe.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Community has contributed debugging for ATMega328P based Arduino or CH32 RISC-V boards, etc.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] A *sketch* is a program written with the Arduino IDE.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Sketches are saved on the development computer as text files with the file extension **.ino**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Arduino Software (IDE) pre-1.0 saved sketches with the extension **.pde**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Most Arduino boards contain a light-emitting diode (LED) and a current-limiting resistor connected between pin 13 and ground, which is a convenient feature for many tests and program functions.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] A typical program used by beginners, akin to Hello, World!, is "blink", which repeatedly blinks the on-board LED integrated into the Arduino board.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] This program uses the functions `pinMode()`, `digitalWrite()`, and `delay()`, which are provided by the internal libraries included in the IDE environment.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] This program is usually loaded into a new Arduino board by the manufacturer.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The open-source nature of the Arduino project has facilitated the publication of many free software libraries that other developers use to augment their projects.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] There is a Xinu OS port for the ATmega328P (Arduino Uno and others with the same chip), which includes most of the basic features.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The source code of this version is freely available.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] There is also a threading tool, named Protothreads.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] Protothreads are described as "extremely lightweight stackless threads designed for severely memory constrained systems, such as small embedded systems or wireless sensor network nodes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] There is a port of FreeRTOS for the Arduino.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] This is available from the Arduino Library Manager.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] It is compatible with a number of boards, including the Uno.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino project received an honorary mention in the Digital Communities category at the 2006 Prix Ars Electronica.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arduino] The Arduino Engineering Kit won the Bett Award for "Higher Education or Further Education Digital Services" in 2020.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] On April 4, 2019, Arris was acquired by network infrastructure provider CommScope.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] Originally named Arris Interactive, the company was founded in 1995 in England and Wales as a joint venture between Nortel Networks and Antec Corp.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] (founded by Anixter in 1991) Bob Stanzione was the founding president and CEO.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] Bruce McClelland took over as CEO on September 1, 2016, with Stanzione becoming executive chairman.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] In 2001, after Antec bought out Nortel's share, the company was renamed Arris Inc, with its executive offices in Suwanee, Georgia, United States.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] On November 8, 2018, CommScope announced an agreement to acquire Arris for $7.4 billion.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] The transaction was completed on April 4, 2019.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] The acquisition doubled CommScope's size, bringing combined revenues to approximately $11.3 billion.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] In the transaction, CommScope also acquired Ruckus Networks and ICX Switch, two companies Arris had recently acquired from Broadcom, with Arris and Ruckus becoming brands of CommScope.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] Former Arris CEO Bruce McClelland assumed the role of CommScope chief operating officer.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] Two of the company's home telephony modems are the TM402P and the TM502G.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] The firm also produces the SBG6580 wireless cable modem-and-router (residential gateway) unit, among other telecommunications and data-transfer products.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] The company has provided products to the Australian National Broadband Network with variants of the Network Termination Device (NBN) that takes the outside connection into the property.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] In November 2001, Arris announced that it would acquire the assets of Cadant Inc., a Naperville, Illinois-based privately held designer and manufacturer of cable modem termination systems.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] The acquisition was completed on January 31, 2002.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] On September 23, 2007, Arris purchased C-COR.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] On September 1, 2009, Arris acquired certain assets of EG Technology, Inc., (EGT), an Atlanta-based company.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] That same month, Arris purchased the assets of Digeo, Inc.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] (including Moxi), for approximately $20 million.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] On October 11, 2011, Arris acquired BigBand Networks, for $172 million, or $53 million net of the estimated cash on hand at BigBand.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] On December 19, 2012, Arris announced that it would acquire Motorola Mobility's home unit (the former General Instrument company) from Google for $2.35 billion in cash and stock.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] The acquisition was completed on April 17, 2013.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] With that acquisition, Arris grew its presence in the set-top box market.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] On April 22, 2015, Arris Group agreed to acquire set-top box manufacturer Pace plc of the United Kingdom, and completed the acquisition on January 4, 2016, in a stock-and-cash deal that valued Pace at £1.4 billion ($2.1 billion).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] Pace shareholders owned 24% of the combined company, and Arris shareholders 76%.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] On February 22, 2017, Arris Group announced an agreement to acquire the Ruckus Wireless unit from Broadcom Inc. for $800 million.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] On August 19, 2014, Arris announced a sponsorship of NASCAR driver Carl Edwards.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] 19 Toyota Camry in the Sprint Cup Series for Joe Gibbs Racing, while Daniel Suárez drove the Arris No.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] 18 in the NASCAR Xfinity Series, from 2015 to 2016 until Edwards left the sport in January 2017.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] In 2017, Arris and Joe Gibbs Racing renewed a multi-year sponsorship agreement.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] Arris sponsored Suárez in 22 races during the 2017 season.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] In 2019, Arris followed Suárez to Stewart–Haas Racing to sponsor the No.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] In January 2019, Arris announced a sponsorship of the Philadelphia Fusion, an e-sports team playing in the Overwatch League.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/arris-international] The contract was extended through the 2020 season.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Such items include mobile phone chargers, cooling fans, portable fridges, electric air pumps, and power inverters.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In most vehicles, at least one car outlet is present.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Some vehicles may have more power outlets: usually one for the front passengers, one for the rear passengers and one for the luggage trunk.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The voltage of the power outlet is usually near 12 V DC, and may be elevated between 13.5 V to 15 V while the engine is running.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] On trucks, the voltage of the power outlet may be near 24 V DC.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The 12 V power circuit is protected by a car fuse, often rated at 10 to 20 amperes, which provides 120 to 240 watts of power.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Large appliances such as hair dryers or toasters draw too much power to be fed from an auxiliary power socket.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] If wired directly rather than through the ignition, an empty car battery can be charged through the outlet from an external power source, which is more convenient albeit slower than currents supported through electrical clamps on the car battery.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Many modern vehicles no longer have the auxiliary power outlet, with it being replaced by USB 2.0 or USB-C ports.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The electrical cigar-lighter was invented and patented in the early 1880s by the Swiss-Austrian inventor Friedrich Wilhelm Schindler.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In the 1890s, these tools were sold as electrical cigar lighters (*Cigarrenanzünder*, later *Zigarrenanzünder*) in the major German warehouse catalogues.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Before the Great Depression, cigarettes overtook cigars in sales, and they became more popularly known as "cigarette lighters", though they have remained the diameter of a standard cigar of 21 millimetres (0.83 in), or a 52 ring gauge.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In 1921, the Morris U.S. patent 1,376,154 was issued for a so-called "wireless" or "cordless" lighter with a removable element.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The igniter was heated in the socket and then manually removed for use after an appropriate time interval.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In the United States, cigarette lighters started appearing in 1925–1926 in some models.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] They were a standard feature by the 1950s.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In 1928, the Connecticut Automotive Specialty Company (Casco) in Bridgeport patented its version of an automotive cigarette lighter, which used a cord and reel.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In the reel-type lighters, the igniter unit was connected with a source of current by a cable that was wound on a spring drum so that the igniter unit and cable could be withdrawn from the socket and be used for lighting a cigar or cigarette.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] As the removable plug was returned to the socket, the wires were reeled back into it.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The circuit was closed either by pressing a button or removing the igniter from its socket.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The modern "automatic" removable automotive V-Coil lighter was developed by Casco in 1956, for which it received U.S. patent 2,959,664, issued in 1960.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The sockets and mating plugs are defined in the ANSI/SAE J563 specification.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] For the 12-volt systems, the center contact is the positive terminal and the shell is the negative terminal.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Most automobiles connect the negative terminal to the frame of the vehicle (negative ground).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] 12-volt auto connectors are made to comply with a standard by Underwriters Laboratories for safety.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] UL2089 was developed to cover the requirements for portable adapters rated 24 V DC or less that are intended to be supplied from the battery-powered electrical system of a vehicle.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Products covered by the standard include cord assemblies of a plug that mates with the standard cigarette receptacle found in automobiles.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Most often used in European automobiles, and sometimes as a second socket in American automobiles expressly for DC power connections.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Plugs often include a pilot light LED indicator to indicate that electrical power is connected.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Optionally, the plug may be equipped with an internal fuse for electrical safety, usually rated at 10 amps or less.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In some designs, the tip of the plug may be unscrewed to reveal a cylindrical glass fuse; other variants may use a blade-type fuse inserted into the side or back of the plug.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The lighter is a metal or plastic cylinder containing a thin flat coil of nichrome metal strip, through which high current (≈10 amperes) passes when the device is activated, usually by pushing it into the socket as though it were a push-button.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] When pushed in, the lighter is held against the force of a spring by a clip attached to a bimetallic strip.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The heating element glows orange hot in seconds, causing the bimetallic strip to bend and release the mechanism.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The handle pops out, eliminating the need for the user to time the heating operation.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] If the lighter is then promptly removed from its socket, it can light a cigarette, cigar, or tinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] A common feature of Italian cars in the 1960s to the 1970s, such as Alfa Romeos and Ferraris, is the Brico Pram cigarette lighter, which differs from conventional designs in that the lighter does not pop out for removal to light a cigarette, even though it visually resembles the traditional design.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The advantage of such a design is in safety as the red-hot heating element cannot be accidentally dropped onto an occupant's lap.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Still, it takes away the ability for the lighter to be removed for the receptacle to be used as a power outlet, and it also does not allow cigars to be lit as the opening is not large enough.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In newer cars, the socket is equipped with a plastic cover without the lighter heating element.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] However, the socket has been repurposed and continues to be used to power consumer electronics in vehicles.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Often, a vehicle may come with several outlets for convenience, some in the rear passenger area of the vehicle or the cargo area, for powering portable devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] These outlets usually have a plastic cap tethered to them, and are usually labeled as being only for DC power, because they are not intended to withstand the heat produced by an electrical cigarette lighter.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The use of cigarette lighter receptacles to supply 12 volt DC power is an example of backward compatibility to a de facto standard.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] As a power connector, the lighter receptacle is larger, harder to use and less reliable than other DC connectors.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] There are two prong threaded plugs to stop the plug from falling out due to vibrations.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Cigarette lighter receptacles are in widespread use in many highway vehicles and some boats.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Portable cigarette lighter receptacles attached to cables and alligator clips for connection directly to car batteries are available for temporary use.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In newer vehicles, one or more USB connectors may also be provided.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Plus in newer cars, the power output from the lighter plug is so reliable that it can charge laptops, without any voltage problems.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Standardized 12 volt DC automobile plugs are defined in the United States by UL Standard 2089 regarding vehicle battery adapters.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] This standard covers plugs and cord sets that insert into cigarette lighter receptacles.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In Europe, 12 volt plugs and sockets are not specially regulated and do not require approvals for the CE mark.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The male plug is sometimes used to feed power *into* a vehicle to recharge its battery because it usually has no regulatory circuitry between the outlet and the car battery.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] For instance, portable solar battery maintainers generally connect to a vehicle's battery in this manner.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Trickle chargers also sometimes connect in this way, eliminating the need to leave a vehicle's hood open, as well as eliminating the possibility of reversed polarity.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Most cars nowadays are designed with a battery-negative earthing system and therefore have a +12V positive power distribution.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In such a case, the centre pin of a plug/socket will be +12V DC and the outer casing 0V.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] While polarity is not an issue for a cigarette lighter, it is prudent to verify the correct matching of polarities when connecting other kinds of accessories.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Since the cigarette lighter socket was originally designed only to heat a cigarette lighter, repurposing these sockets as generic power connectors can lead to many problems.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] In addition to the issues with partially-compatible physical dimensions, the plugs can vibrate out of the socket under normal driving conditions, owing to poor retention.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Also, there have been reports of melted plug tips due to poor contact and heat generation from ohmic resistance.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] A second problem is that nominally "twelve-volt" power in cars fluctuates widely.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The outlet is connected directly to the electrical system of the car.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] When used, DC to DC converters will usually compensate for small fluctuations, but reliable power may not be available without an independent battery-powered uninterruptible power supply.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Rarely, more extreme cases of voltage fluctuation can occur when the car battery is disconnected while the engine is running, or when the car receives a jump start.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] The load dump transient may also ruin the diodes in the alternator by exceeding their breakdown voltage.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] A car receiving a jump start from a truck may be subject to a 24 V electrical system used in some vehicles.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Also, a "double battery jump-start" is performed by some tow truck drivers in cold climates.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Equipment intended to be powered by the receptacle needs to account for intermittent contact, and voltages outside the nominal 12 V DC, such as maximum voltage 9–16 V continuously, or maximum voltage of 20 V lasting 1 hour, 24 V lasting 1 minute, and 40 V lasting 400 ms.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] An example of protection component ratings tolerance is +50 to −60 V DC.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cigarette-lighter-receptacle] Robust equipment must tolerate temperatures varying between −40 and +85 °C (−40 and 185 °F), plus possible high humidity and condensation of water.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] A **coaxial power connector** is an electrical power connector used for attaching extra-low voltage devices such as consumer electronics to external electricity.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Also known as **barrel connectors**, **concentric barrel connectors** or **tip connectors**, these small cylindrical connectors come in an enormous variety of sizes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Barrel plug connectors are commonly used to interface the secondary side of a power supply with the device.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Some of these jacks contain a normally closed switch; the switch can disconnect internal batteries whenever the external power supply is connected.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The connector pairs for barrel connectors are defined in terms of "plugs" and "receptacles"; receptacles are more commonly called "sockets" or "jacks" in the United States.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Receptacles may be panel-mounted or circuit board-mounted.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Some in-line receptacles are also cable-mounted.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Power is generally supplied by a plug to a receptacle.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Cables are available with one in-line receptacle fanning out to several plugs, so that many devices may be supplied by one supply.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] As the use of a plug implies a cable, even a short stub, some power supplies carry panel-mounted receptacles instead to avoid this cable.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Cables for such cases are available with a plug at each end, although cables or adapters with two receptacles are not widely available.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] On the plug, the outer body terminal is metallic and cylindrical in shape and comprises one of the two contacts.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The second, inside contact is a hollow metallic cylinder constructed to accept insertion of the pin in the corresponding socket.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The inner and outer barrels are separated by an insulating layer, which is flared at the tip to prevent a short circuit when the plug is inserted or removed.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The outer terminal is usually the GND pin, and inner is Vn+ is a voltage supply pin, where *n* voltage is 5V, 12V, 24V, etc..
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] This less common type of plug is similar to the female version, but the center pin is of male type.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] There is typically a single spring-loaded contact at the side of the socket and a pin in the center in order to connect the female type plug.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The socket or receptacle for connecting the male-type plug has, instead, a ring in the middle.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] There are many different sizes of coaxial power connectors.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] See the table at the end of this article.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Contact ratings commonly vary from unspecified up to 5 A (11 A for special high-power versions).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Voltage is often unspecified, but may be up to 48 V with 12 V typical.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The smaller types usually have lower current and voltage ratings.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] It is quite possible that new sizes will continue to appear and disappear.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] One possible reason that a particular manufacturer may use a new size is to discourage use of third-party power supplies, either for technical reasons or to force use of their own accessories, or both.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The sizes and shapes of connectors do not consistently correspond to the same power specifications across manufacturers and models.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Two connectors from different manufacturers with different sizes could potentially be attached to power supplies with the same voltage and current.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Alternatively, connectors of the same size can be part of power supplies with different voltages and currents.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Use of the wrong power supply may cause severe equipment damage or even fire.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Generic plugs are often described by their inside diameter, such as *2.1 mm DC plugs*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] After the two common 5.5 mm **OD** (Outer Diameter) plugs, the next-most common size is 3.5 mm OD with a 1.3 mm **ID** (Inner Diameter), usually about 9.5 mm in length, although both longer and shorter versions also exist.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] These 3.5 mm OD plugs are normally used for lower voltages and currents.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] A ring-shaped "locking detent" or "high-retention feature", present on the barrel of some DC coaxial connectors, is a feature intended to prevent accidental disconnection.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Typically, this feature is a conical cut-back section of the tip, just behind the insulator that separates the inner from the outer contact surfaces.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] A "lock-ring DC coaxial connector" uses a captive threaded ring or collar to secure the connection between the plug and jack.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] This design offers strong resistance to unplugging when used properly.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] A "lock-tab DC coaxial connector" (also called "bayonet lock") offers a compromise that resists unplugging, but which will disengage when pulled hard enough.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] This connector uses small metal tab protrusions on the connector barrel to lock the plug in place, requiring a special push-and-rotate motion to engage the locks.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] There are several standards in existence, provided by bodies such as the IEC, EIAJ in Japan and DIN in Germany.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] More recently, some manufacturers appear to have implemented their own system correlating voltage and plug size.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] In addition, there appears to be a trend to standardize DC connector to negative **barrel** (or sleeve) of a coaxial power connector.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The Japanese trade organization EIAJ issued EIAJ RC-5320A, which defines five plug and matching socket or jack sizes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Each of these plugs is used with a specified voltage range.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Most manufacturers use colored insulating materials to distinguish these plugs from other similar-looking DC plugs, and for quick identification between EIAJ plugs of similar size.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] EIAJ-04 and 05 have an internal male pin in the plug.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The 01 through 03 sizes do not and are similar to the generic plugs in structure.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] These five EIAJ plugs are 9.5 mm in length and have a current rating of 2A.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] There are two other, less common, connectors defined by EIAJ; RC-5321 and RC-5322.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The latter is designed for both 12 V and 24 V automotive applications.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The German national standards organization DIN (Deutsches Institut für Normung—German Institute for Standardization) issued DIN 45323 in 1982 and since withdrawn, which defines two DC power plug and jack (respectively) sizes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] At least one of these sizes has a maximum rating of 34 V and 3 A.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] The information here is inferred from catalog references, as the German standard has not been translated into English yet.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] This list attempts to show all known sizes, and is annotated with some manufacturers producing selected types, since each manufacturer makes its own unique subset of the known types.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Note that the example part numbers given may have different connector barrel (sleeve) lengths, and are not necessarily exact equivalents.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] There are many more design variants than can be listed in this table, so only a small sampling of part numbers is given.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Connector size is often listed in the format OD (outer diameter) × ID (inner diameter) × L (length of barrel) and expressed in millimeters.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Designations may vary between manufacturers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Coaxial plugs that have a male center pin will have another measurement, Center Pin Diameter (CPD).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] These plugs are often used for higher power applications such as portable computers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Used in satellite radio docks and other devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] Philmore Coaxial Power Plug 3.0mm I.D./5.5mm O.D.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/coaxial-power-connector] ES2 and M365 electric scooters & Goal Zero Solar devices (Sherpa & Yeti).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Radio broadcasting in the early 20th century brought the first major consumer product, the broadcast receiver.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Later products included telephones, televisions, calculators, cameras, video game consoles, mobile phones, personal computers, and MP3 players.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In the 2010s, consumer electronics stores often sold GPS, automotive electronics (vehicle audio), video game consoles, electronic musical instruments such as synthesizer keyboards, karaoke machines, digital cameras, and video players.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Such video playing equipment included VCRs in the 1980s and 1990s, and eventually DVD players and Blu-ray players.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Stores also sold smart light fixtures, network devices, camcorders, and smartphones.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Some of the modern products being sold include virtual reality goggles, smart home devices that connect to the Internet, streaming devices, and wearable technology.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In the 2010s, most consumer electronics were based on digital technologies and increasingly merged with the computer and video game industry, in a trend often referred to as the consumerization of information technology.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Some consumer electronics stores also began selling office and baby furniture.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Consumer electronics stores may be physical "brick and mortar" retail stores, online stores, or combinations of both.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Annual consumer electronics sales were expected to reach $2.9 trillion by 2020.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The sector is part of the electronics industry, which is, in turn, driven by the semiconductor industry.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] For its first fifty years, the phonograph turntable did not use electronics; the needle and sound horn were purely mechanical technologies.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] However, in the 1920s, radio broadcasting became the basis of the mass production of radio receivers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The vacuum tubes that had made radios practical were used with record players as well.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] This was to amplify the sound so that it could be played through a loudspeaker.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Television was invented soon after, but remained insignificant in the consumer market until the 1950s.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The first working transistor, a point-contact transistor, was invented by John Bardeen and Walter Houser Brattain at Bell Labs in 1947, which led to significant research in the field of solid-state semiconductors in the early-1950s.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The invention and development of the earliest transistors at Bell led to transistor radios, in turn promoting the emergence of the home entertainment consumer electronics industry starting in the 1950s.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] This was largely due to the efforts of Tokyo Tsushin Kogyo (now Sony) in successfully commercializing transistor technology for a mass market, with affordable transistor radios and then transistorized television sets.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Integrated circuits (ICs) followed when manufacturers built circuits (usually for military purposes) on a single substrate using electrical connections between circuits within the chip itself.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] IC technology led to more advanced and cheaper consumer electronics, such as transistorized televisions, pocket calculators, and by the 1980s, video game consoles and personal computers affordable for regular middle-class families.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Beginning in the 1980s and continuing through the early 2000s, many consumer electronics, such as televisions and stereo systems, underwent digitization.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The introduction of compact discs (CDs) and personal computers during this period signalled a broader shift as digital computer technology and digital signals were increasingly integrated into consumer devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] This transformation significantly altered their functionality and led to improved performance, such as enhanced image quality in televisions.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] These advancements were largely driven by Moore’s Law, which enabled rapid increases in processing power and reductions in cost and size.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In 2004, the consumer electronics industry was worth US $240 billion annually worldwide, comprising visual equipment, audio equipment, and games consoles.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The industry became global, with Asia Pacific having a 35% market share, Europe having 31.5%, the US having 23%, and the rest of the world owning the remainder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Major players in this industry are household names like Sony, Samsung, Philips, Sanyo, and Sharp.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The increase in popularity of such domestic appliances as 'white goods' is a characteristic element of consumption patterns during the golden age of the Western economy.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Europe's White Goods industry has evolved over the past 40 years, first by changing tariff barriers, and later by technical and demand shifts.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The spending on domestic appliances has claimed only a tiny fraction of disposable income, rising from 0.5 percent in the US in 1920 to about 2 percent in 1980.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Yet, the sequence of electrical and mechanical durables have altered the activities and experiences of households in America and Britain in the twentieth century.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] With the expansion of cookers, vacuum cleaners, refrigerators, washing machines, radios, televisions, air conditioning, and microwave ovens, households have gained an escalating number of appliances.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Despite the ubiquity of these goods, their diffusion is not well understood.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Some types of appliances diffuse more frequently than others.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Consumer electronics products such as the digital distribution of video games have become increasingly based on the internet and digital technologies.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The consumer electronics industry has primarily merged with the software industry in what is increasingly referred to as the consumerization of information technology.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] One overriding characteristic of consumer electronic products is the trend of ever-falling prices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] This is driven by gains in manufacturing efficiency and automation, lower labor costs as manufacturing has moved to lower-wage countries, and improvements in semiconductor design.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Semiconductor components benefit from Moore's law, an observed principle which states that, for a given price, semiconductor functionality doubles every two years.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Although consumer electronics shows a trend towards convergence, consumers still face varied purchasing decisions.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Product information therefore needs to remain current and comparable for the consumer to support informed choices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Factors such as style, price, specification, and performance all play a role in these decisions.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] At the same time, there is a gradual shift towards e-commerce web-storefronts.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Many products include Internet access using technologies such as Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, EDGE, or Ethernet.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Products not traditionally associated with computer use (such as TVs or Hi-fi equipment) now provide options to connect to the Internet or to a computer using a home network to provide access to digital content.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The desire for high-definition (HD) content has led the industry to develop a number of technologies, such as WirelessHD or ITU-T G.hn, which are optimized for distribution of HD content between consumer electronic devices in a home.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The consumer electronics industry faces consumers with unpredictable tastes on the demand side, supplier-related delays or disruptions on the supply side, and production challenges occurring in the process.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The high rate of technology evolution or revolution requires large investments without any guarantee of profitable returns.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] As a result, the big players rely on global markets to achieve economies of scale.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Even these companies sometimes have to cooperate with each other, for instance on standards, to reduce the risk of their investments.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In supply chain management, there is much discussion on risks related to such aspects of supply chains as short product lifecycles, high competition combined with cooperation, and globalization.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The consumer electronics industry is the very embodiment of these aspects of supply chain management and related risks.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] While some of the supply and demand related risks are similar to such industries as the toy industry, the consumer electronics industry faces additional risks due to its vertically integrated supply chains.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] There are also numerous supply-chain-wide contextual risks that cut across the supply chain especially impacting companies with global supply chains.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] These include cultural differences in multinational operations, environmental risk, regulations risk, and exchange rate risk across multiple countries.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Whether or not demand is comparable across countries affects the extent of the gains from international integration.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In addition, consumer preferences change over time to disturb existing patterns of behavior.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] A feature of some industries is that demand for variety increases as the market moves from first-time buying to replacement demand.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] A resource to further understand this idea of consumer preferences can be observed through Lizabeth Cohen's book titled, "A Consumers' Republic", "Only if we have large demands can we expect large production".
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The electronics industry, especially consumer electronics, emerged in the 20th century and has become a global industry worth billions of dollars.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Contemporary society uses all manner of electronic devices built-in automated or semi-automated factories operated by the industry.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Most consumer electronics are manufactured in China, due to maintenance cost, availability of materials, quality, and speed as opposed to other countries such as the United States.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Cities such as Shenzhen and Dongguan have become important production centers for the industry, attracting many consumer electronics companies such as Apple Inc.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] An electronic component is any essential discrete device or physical entity in an electronic system used to affect electrons or their associated fields.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Electronic components are mostly industrial products, available in a singular form, and are not to be confused with electrical elements, conceptual abstractions representing idealized electronic components.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Consumer electronics such as personal computers use various types of software.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Embedded software is used within some consumer electronics, such as mobile phones.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] This type of software may be embedded within the hardware of electronic devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Some consumer electronics include software that is used on a personal computer in conjunction with electronic devices, such as camcorders and digital cameras, and third-party software for such devices also exists.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Some consumer electronics adhere to protocols, such as connection protocols "to high speed bi-directional signals".
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In telecommunications, a communications protocol is a system of digital rules for data exchange within or between computers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The Consumer Electronics Show (CES) trade show has taken place yearly in Las Vegas, Nevada since its foundation in 1973.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The event, which grew from having 100 exhibitors in its inaugural year to more than 4,500 exhibiting companies in its 2020 edition, features the latest in consumer electronics, speeches by industry experts and innovation awards.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The IFA Berlin trade show has taken place in Berlin, Germany since its foundation in 1924.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The event features new consumer electronics and speeches by industry pioneers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), the world's largest professional society, has many initiatives to advance the state of the art of consumer electronics.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] IEEE has a dedicated society of thousands of professionals to promote CE, called the Consumer Electronics Society (CESoc).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] IEEE has multiple periodicals and international conferences to promote CE and encourage collaborative research and development in CE.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The flagship conference of CESoc, called IEEE International Conference on Consumer Electronics (ICCE), is in its 35th year.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) Computer Society also have initiated a conference to research on next generation consumer electronics as Smart Electronics.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The conference, named IEEE Symposium on Smart Electronics Systems (IEEE-iSES) is on its 9th year.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Electronics retailing is a significant part of the retail industry in many countries.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Broad-based retailers, such as Walmart and Target, also sell consumer electronics in many of their stores.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In April 2014, retail e-commerce sales were the highest in the consumer electronic and computer categories as well.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Some consumer electronics retailers offer extended warranties on products with programs such as *SquareTrade*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] An electronics district is an area of commerce with a high density of retail stores that sell consumer electronics.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Consumer electronic service can refer to the maintenance of said products.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] When consumer electronics have malfunctions, they may sometimes be repaired.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In 2013, in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, the increased popularity in listening to sound from analog audio devices, such as phonographs, as opposed to digital sound, has sparked a noticeable increase of business for the electronic repair industry there.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] A mobile phone, cellular phone, cell phone, cellphone, handphone, or hand phone, sometimes shortened to simply mobile, cell or just phone, is a portable telephone that can make and receive calls over a radio frequency link while the user is moving within a telephone service area.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The radio frequency link establishes a connection to the switching systems of a mobile phone operator, which provides access to the public switched telephone network (PSTN).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Modern mobile telephone services use a cellular network architecture and, therefore, mobile telephones are called *cellular telephones* or *cell phones* in North America.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In addition to telephony, digital mobile phones (2G) support a variety of other services, such as text messaging, MMS, email, Internet access, short-range wireless communications (infrared, Bluetooth), business applications, video games and digital photography.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Mobile phones offering only those capabilities are known as feature phones; mobile phones which offer greatly advanced computing capabilities are referred to as smartphones.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] A smartphone is a portable device that combines mobile telephone and computing functions into one unit.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] In 2017, Greenpeace USA published a study of 17 of the world's leading consumer electronics companies about their energy and resource consumption and the use of chemicals.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Electronic devices use thousands of rare metals and rare earth elements (40 on average for a smartphone), these materials are extracted and refined using water and energy-intensive processes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] These metals are also used in the renewable energy industry meaning that consumer electronics are directly competing for the raw materials.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The energy consumption of consumer electronics and their environmental impact, either from their production processes or the disposal of the devices, is increasing steadily.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] EIA estimates that electronic devices and gadgets account for about 10%–15% of the energy use in American homes – largely because of their number; the average house has dozens of electronic devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The energy consumption of consumer electronics increases – in America and Europe – to about 50% of household consumption if the term is redefined to include home appliances such as refrigerators, dryers, clothes washers and dishwashers.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Standby power – used by consumer electronics and appliances while they are turned off – accounts for 5–10% of total household energy consumption, costing $100 annually to the average household in the United States.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] A study by United States Department of Energy's Berkeley Lab found that videocassette recorders (VCRs) consume more electricity during the course of a year in standby mode than when they are used to record or playback videos.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Similar findings were obtained concerning satellite boxes, which consume almost the same amount of energy in "on" and "off" modes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] A 2012 study in the United Kingdom, carried out by the Energy Saving Trust, found that the devices using the most power on standby mode included televisions, satellite boxes, and other video and audio equipment.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The study concluded that UK households could save up to £86 per year by switching devices off instead of using standby mode.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] A report from the International Energy Agency in 2014 found that $80 billion of power is wasted globally per year due to inefficiency of electronic devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Consumers can reduce unwanted use of standby power by unplugging their devices, using power strips with switches, or by buying devices that are standardized for better energy management, particularly Energy Star-marked products.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] A high number of different metals and low concentration rates in electronics means that recycling is limited and energy intensive.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Electronic waste describes discarded electrical or electronic devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Many consumer electronics may contain toxic minerals and elements, and many electronic scrap components, such as CRTs, may contain contaminants such as lead, cadmium, beryllium, mercury, dioxins, or brominated flame retardants.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Electronic waste recycling may involve significant risk to workers and communities and great care must be taken to avoid unsafe exposure in recycling operations and leaking of materials such as heavy metals from landfills and incinerator ashes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] However, large amounts of the produced electronic waste from developed countries is exported, and handled by the informal sector in countries like India, despite the fact that exporting electronic waste to them is illegal.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Strong informal sector can be a problem for the safe and clean recycling.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] E-waste policies have evolved since the 1970s, with priorities shifting over time.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Initially, the focus was on safer disposal methods due to the toxic materials often found in electronic waste.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Over the years, attention turned to the recovery of valuable metals and plastics that could be recycled.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] More recently, the emphasis has shifted once again, this time toward reusing entire devices.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] New guidelines promoting 'preparation for reuse' highlight the growing importance of repair and reuse, signaling a gradual change in public and policy attitudes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] With turnover of small household appliances high and costs relatively low, many consumers will throw unwanted electrical goods in the normal dustbin, meaning that items of potentially high reuse or recycling value go to landfills.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] While more oversized items such as washing machines are usually collected, it has been estimated that the 160,000 tonnes of EEE in regular waste collections were worth £220 million.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] 23% of EEE (Electrical and electronic equipment) taken to Household Waste Recycling Centres was immediately resalable – or would be with minor repairs or refurbishment.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] This indicates a lack of awareness among consumers about where and how to dispose of EEE and the potential value of things that are going in the bin.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] For the reuse and repair of electrical goods to increase substantially in the UK, some barriers must be overcome.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] These include people's mistrust of used equipment in terms of whether it will be functional, safe and the stigma for some of owning second-hand goods.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] But the benefits of reuse could allow lower-income households access to previously unaffordable technology while helping the environment at the same time.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Desktop monitors and laptops can contribute to major physical health concerns known as repetitive strain injuries.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] For example, when users are forced to bend to see electronic screens better, they may experience chronic neck and back pains.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] The best-known disease in this category is carpal tunnel syndrome.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Other conditions include de Quervain syndrome, a condition that affects tendons in the thumb.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Electronic use before bed is also associated with poorer sleep quality and sleep duration.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/consumer-electronics] Poor quality, shorter sleep is associated with various health conditions such as obesity and diabetes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A **cylinder** (from Ancient Greek κύλινδρος*(*kúlindros*)* 'roller, tumbler') has traditionally been a three-dimensional solid, one of the most basic of curvilinear geometric shapes.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] In elementary geometry, it is considered a prism with a circle as its base.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A cylinder may also be defined as an infinite curvilinear surface in various modern branches of geometry and topology.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The shift in the basic meaning—solid versus surface (as in a solid ball versus sphere surface)—has created some ambiguity with terminology.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The two concepts may be distinguished by referring to **solid cylinders** and **cylindrical surfaces**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] In the literature the unadorned term "cylinder" could refer to either of these or to an even more specialized object, the *right circular cylinder*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A **cylindrical surface** is a surface consisting of all the points on all the lines which are parallel to a given line and which pass through a fixed plane curve in a plane not parallel to the given line.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Any line in this family of parallel lines is called an *element* of the cylindrical surface.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] From a kinematics point of view, given a plane curve, called the *directrix*, a cylindrical surface is that surface traced out by a line, called the *generatrix*, not in the plane of the directrix, moving parallel to itself and always passing through the directrix.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Any particular position of the generatrix is an element of the cylindrical surface.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A solid bounded by a cylindrical surface and two parallel planes is called a (solid) **cylinder**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The line segments determined by an element of the cylindrical surface between the two parallel planes are called an *element of the cylinder*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] All the elements of a cylinder have equal lengths.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The region bounded by the cylindrical surface in either of the parallel planes is called a **base** of the cylinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The two bases of a cylinder are congruent figures.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] If the elements of the cylinder are perpendicular to the planes containing the bases, the cylinder is a **right cylinder**, otherwise it is called an **oblique cylinder**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] If the bases are disks (regions whose boundary is a circle) the cylinder is called a **circular cylinder**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] In some elementary treatments, a cylinder always means a circular cylinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] An **open cylinder** is a cylindrical surface without the bases.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The **height** (or altitude) of a cylinder is the perpendicular distance between its bases.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The cylinder obtained by rotating a line segment about a fixed line that it is parallel to is a **cylinder of revolution**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A cylinder of revolution is a right circular cylinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The height of a cylinder of revolution is the length of the generating line segment.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The line that the segment is revolved about is called the **axis** of the cylinder and it passes through the centers of the two bases.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The bare term *cylinder* often refers to a solid cylinder with circular ends perpendicular to the axis, that is, a right circular cylinder, as shown in the figure.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The cylindrical surface without the ends is called an **open cylinder**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The formulae for the surface area and the volume of a right circular cylinder have been known from early antiquity.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A right circular cylinder can also be thought of as the solid of revolution generated by rotating a rectangle about one of its sides.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] These cylinders are used in an integration technique (the "disk method") for obtaining volumes of solids of revolution.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A tall and thin *needle cylinder* has a height much greater than its diameter, whereas a short and wide *disk cylinder* has a diameter much greater than its height.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A cylindric section is the intersection of a cylinder's surface with a plane.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] They are, in general, curves and are special types of *plane sections*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The cylindric section by a plane that contains two elements of a cylinder is a parallelogram.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Such a cylindric section of a right cylinder is a rectangle.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A cylindric section in which the intersecting plane intersects and is perpendicular to all the elements of the cylinder is called a **right section**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] If a right section of a cylinder is a circle then the cylinder is a circular cylinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] In more generality, if a right section of a cylinder is a conic section (parabola, ellipse, hyperbola) then the solid cylinder is said to be parabolic, elliptic and hyperbolic, respectively.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] For a right circular cylinder, there are several ways in which planes can meet a cylinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] First, planes that intersect a base in at most one point.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A plane is tangent to the cylinder if it meets the cylinder in a single element.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The right sections are circles and all other planes intersect the cylindrical surface in an ellipse.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] If a plane intersects a base of the cylinder in exactly two points then the line segment joining these points is part of the cylindric section.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] If such a plane contains two elements, it has a rectangle as a cylindric section, otherwise the sides of the cylindric section are portions of an ellipse.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Finally, if a plane contains more than two points of a base, it contains the entire base and the cylindric section is a circle.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] This formula holds whether or not the cylinder is a right cylinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] This formula may be established by using Cavalieri's principle.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] In more generality, by the same principle, the volume of any cylinder is the product of the area of a base and the height.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] For example, an elliptic cylinder with a base having semi-major axis a, semi-minor axis b and height h has a volume *V* = *Ah*, where A is the area of the base ellipse (= π*ab*).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The area of the top and bottom bases is the same, and is called the *base area*, *B*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The area of the side is known as the **lateral area**, *L*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The surface area of the solid right circular cylinder is made up the sum of all three components: top, bottom and side.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Its surface area is therefore $A=L+2B=2\pi rh+2\pi r^{2}=2\pi r(h+r)=\pi d(r+h)$ where *d* = 2*r* is the diameter of the circular top or bottom.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] For a given volume, the right circular cylinder with the smallest surface area has *h* = 2*r*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Equivalently, for a given surface area, the right circular cylinder with the largest volume has *h* = 2*r*, that is, the cylinder fits snugly in a cube of side length = altitude ( = diameter of base circle).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The lateral area, L, of a circular cylinder, which need not be a right cylinder, is more generally given by $L=e\times p,$ where e is the length of an element and p is the perimeter of a right section of the cylinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] This produces the previous formula for lateral area when the cylinder is a right circular cylinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A *right circular hollow cylinder* (or **cylindrical shell**) is a three-dimensional region bounded by two right circular cylinders having the same axis and two parallel annular bases perpendicular to the cylinders' common axis, as in the diagram.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Let the height be *h*, internal radius *r*, and external radius *R*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The surface area, including the top and bottom, is given by $A=2\pi \left(R+r\right)h+2\pi \left(R^{2}-r^{2}\right).$ Cylindrical shells are used in a common integration technique for finding volumes of solids of revolution.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] In the treatise by this name, written c.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] 225 BCE, Archimedes obtained the result of which he was most proud, namely obtaining the formulas for the volume and surface area of a sphere by exploiting the relationship between a sphere and its circumscribed right circular cylinder of the same height and diameter.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The sphere has a volume two-thirds that of the circumscribed cylinder and a surface area two-thirds that of the cylinder (including the bases).
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Since the values for the cylinder were already known, he obtained, for the first time, the corresponding values for the sphere.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A sculpted sphere and cylinder were placed on the tomb of Archimedes at his request.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] In some areas of geometry and topology the term *cylinder* refers to what has been called a **cylindrical surface**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A cylinder is defined as a surface consisting of all the points on all the lines which are parallel to a given line and which pass through a fixed plane curve in a plane not parallel to the given line.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Such cylinders have, at times, been referred to as **generalized cylinders**.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Through each point of a generalized cylinder there passes a unique line that is contained in the cylinder.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Thus, this definition may be rephrased to say that a cylinder is any ruled surface spanned by a one-parameter family of parallel lines.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A cylinder having a right section that is an ellipse, parabola, or hyperbola is called an **elliptic cylinder**, **parabolic cylinder** and **hyperbolic cylinder**, respectively.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] When the principal axes of a quadric are aligned with the reference frame (always possible for a quadric), a general equation of the quadric in three dimensions is given by $f(x,y,z)=Ax^{2}+By^{2}+Cz^{2}+Dx+Ey+Gz+H=0,$ with the coefficients being real numbers and not all of A, B and C being 0.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] If at least one variable does not appear in the equation, then the quadric is degenerate.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] If *AB* > 0 this is the equation of an *elliptic cylinder*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Further simplification can be obtained by translation of axes and scalar multiplication.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Elliptic cylinders are also known as *cylindroids*, but that name is ambiguous, as it can also refer to the Plücker conoid.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] If $\rho$ has a different sign than the coefficients, we obtain the *imaginary elliptic cylinders*: $\left({\frac {x}{a}}\right)^{2}+\left({\frac {y}{b}}\right)^{2}=-1,$ which have no real points on them.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] In projective geometry, a cylinder is simply a cone whose apex (vertex) lies on the plane at infinity.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] If the cone is a quadratic cone, the plane at infinity (which passes through the vertex) can intersect the cone at two real lines, a single real line (actually a coincident pair of lines), or only at the vertex.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] These cases give rise to the hyperbolic, parabolic or elliptic cylinders respectively.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] This concept is useful when considering degenerate conics, which may include the cylindrical conics.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] A *solid circular cylinder* can be regarded as the limiting case of a n-gonal prism as n approaches infinity.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Because of this close relationship, many earlier geometry texts treat prisms and cylinders together.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Standard formulas for the surface area and volume of a cylinder can be derived from the corresponding formulas for prisms by considering inscribed and circumscribed prisms and taking the limit as the number of sides increases without bound.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] The focus on circular cylinders in classical treatments arises from the fact that a circular base is the only plane figure for which this limiting argument can be carried out using elementary methods, without relying on calculus.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] Cylinders and prisms also share parallel terminology: for example, a *truncated prism* is a prism whose bases do not lie in parallel planes, and by analogy a solid cylinder with non-parallel bases is called a *truncated cylinder*.
[src:coaxial-power-connector/cylindrical] From a polyhedral perspective, a cylinder may also be viewed as the dual of a bicone, interpreted as an infinite-sided bipyramid.
